<?xml version="1.0" encoding="UTF-8"?>

<section xml:id="sec-definition-of-continuity-examples"
  xmlns:xi="http://www.w3.org/2001/XInclude">
  <title>Definition of Continuity. Examples.</title>

  <subsection xml:id="subsec-continuity-at-a-point">
    <title>Continuity at a Point</title>

    <p>
      Let <m>S \subseteq \R</m> and let <m>f \colon S \to \R</m>
      be a function. We say that <m>f</m> is <term>continuous
      at</term><idx>continuous at a point</idx> <m>c \in S</m> if for
      every <m>\varepsilon \gt 0</m> there exists <m>\delta \gt 0</m> such
      that whenever <m>x \in S</m> and <m>|x-c| \lt \delta</m>, we have
      <me>|f(x)-f(c)| \lt \varepsilon.</me>
      In other words, <m>f</m> is continuous at <m>c</m> if the output
      <m>f(x)</m> can be made arbitrarily close to <m>f(c)</m> provided that
      the input <m>x</m> is sufficiently close to <m>c</m>.
    </p>

    <p>
      If <m>A \subseteq S</m>, then <m>f</m> is <term>continuous
      on</term><idx>continuous on a set</idx> <m>A</m> if it is continuous at
      every point of <m>A</m>. We say simply that <m>f</m> is
      <term>continuous</term><idx>continuous function</idx> if it is
      continuous on its whole domain.
    </p>

    <p>
      The definition only refers to points <m>x</m> that lie in the domain
      <m>S</m>. So continuity at <m>c</m> concerns the behavior of <m>f</m>
      on domain points near <m>c</m>; we do not need <m>f</m> to be defined
      on an entire open interval around <m>c</m>.
    </p>
  </subsection>

  <subsection xml:id="subsec-cluster-and-isolated-points">
    <title>Cluster Points and Isolated Points</title>

    <p>
      A <term>neighborhood</term> of a point <m>c \in \R</m> is a subset
      of <m>\R</m> that contains an open interval around <m>c</m>.
      In particular, every open interval containing <m>c</m> is a neighborhood
      of <m>c</m>.
    </p>

    <p>
      Let <m>S \subseteq \R</m>. A real number <m>c</m> is called a
      <term>cluster point</term><idx>cluster point</idx> of <m>S</m> if for
      every <m>\delta \gt 0</m> there exists <m>x \in S</m> such that <m>x
      \neq c</m> and <m>|x-c| \lt \delta</m>. In other words, <m>c</m> is a
      cluster point of <m>S</m> if every neighborhood of <m>c</m> contains
      a point in <m>S</m> other than <m>c</m>. A point <m>c \in S</m> is an
      <term>isolated point</term><idx>isolated point</idx> of <m>S</m> if it
      is not a cluster point of <m>S</m>. That is, there exists <m>\delta \gt
      0</m> such that <me>S \cap (c-\delta,c+\delta)=\{c\}.</me> Equivalently,
      some neighborhood of <m>c</m> contains no points of <m>S</m> other than
      <m>c</m>. A cluster point of <m>S</m> need not belong to <m>S</m>, but
      an isolated point of <m>S</m>, by definition, must belong to <m>S</m>.
    </p>

    <example xml:id="eg-cluster-and-isolated-points">
      <statement>
        <ul>
          <li>
            Every point of an open interval <m>(a,b)</m> is a cluster point
            of <m>(a,b)</m>.
          </li>
          <li>
            The point <m>0</m> is a cluster point of <m>(0,1)</m> even though
            <m>0 \notin (0,1)</m>.
          </li>
          <li>
            Every integer is an isolated point of <m>\Z</m>.
          </li>
          <li>
            In the set <m>\{0\} \cup \{1/n : n \in \N\}</m>, the point
            <m>0</m> is a cluster point, while each point <m>1/n</m> is an
            isolated point.
          </li>
        </ul>
      </statement>
    </example>

    <proposition xml:id="prop-isolated-points-are-continuity-points">
      <statement>
        <p>
          A function is continuous at the isolated points of its domain.
        </p>
      </statement>

      <proof>
        <p>
          Let <m>c</m> be an isolated point of the domain <m>S</m> of a
          function <m>f</m>. Then there exists some <m>\delta_0 \gt 0</m>
          such that <m>S \cap (c-\delta_0,c+\delta_0)=\{c\}</m>. So whenever
          <m>x \in S</m> and <m>|x-c| \lt \delta_0</m>, necessarily
          <m>x=c</m>. Hence,
          <me>|f(x)-f(c)|=|f(c)-f(c)|=0</me>
          which is less than any positive <m>\varepsilon</m>. This shows that
          <m>f</m> is continuous at <m>c</m>.
        </p>
      </proof>
    </proposition>

    <p>
        A cluster point is also called a <term>limit point</term><idx>limit
	point</idx>. Here is why:
    </p>

    <proposition>
      <statement>
        <p>
          A real number <m>c</m> is a cluster point of <m>S \subseteq \R</m>
          if and only if there is an injective sequence <m>(x_n)</m> in
          <m>S</m> that converges to <m>c</m>.
        </p>
      </statement>

      <proof>
        <p>
          First suppose that <m>c</m> is a cluster point of <m>S</m>. We
          construct an injective sequence <m>(x_n)</m> in <m>S</m> such that
          <m>x_n \to c</m>. Since <m>c</m> is a cluster point, there exists
          <m>x_1 \in S</m> such that <m>0 \lt |x_1-c| \lt 1</m>. Now suppose
          that <m>x_1,\dots,x_{n-1}</m> have been chosen in <m>S</m>, all
          distinct, with <m>0 \lt |x_k-c| \lt 1/k</m> for
          <m>k=1,\dots,n-1</m>. Let
          <me>\eta=\min\{|x_1-c|,\dots,|x_{n-1}-c|\} \gt 0.</me>
          Because <m>c</m> is a cluster point of <m>S</m>, there exists
          <m>x_n \in S</m> such that
          <me>0 \lt |x_n-c| \lt \min\{1/n,\eta\}.</me>
          Then <m>x_n \neq x_k</m> for <m>k=1,\dots,n-1</m>, because
          <m>|x_n-c| \lt |x_k-c|</m>. Thus, by induction, we obtain an
          injective sequence <m>(x_n)</m> in <m>S</m> with
          <m>|x_n-c| \lt 1/n</m> for every <m>n</m>. Since <m>1/n \to 0</m>,
          it follows that <m>|x_n-c| \to 0</m>, and hence <m>x_n \to c</m>.
        </p>

	<p>
	  Conversely, suppose there is an injective sequence <m>(x_n)</m> in
	  <m>S</m> such that <m>x_n \to c</m>. Let <m>\delta \gt 0</m>. Since
	  <m>x_n \to c</m>, <m>|x_n-c| \lt \delta</m> for all <m>n</m>
	  sufficiently large. In particular, the inequality is satisfied
	  by infinitely many terms of the sequence. At most one of them
	  can be <m>c</m> by injectivity. Therefore, <m>x_N \neq c</m> for
	  some sufficiently large <m>N</m> and so <m>|x_N-c| \lt \delta</m>
	  as well. This shows that every neighborhood of <m>c</m> contains
	  a point of <m>S</m> other than <m>c</m>. Therefore <m>c</m> is a
	  cluster point of <m>S</m>.
	</p>
      </proof>
    </proposition>
  </subsection>

  <subsection xml:id="subsec-examples-of-continuous-functions">
    <title>Examples of Continuous Functions</title>

    <p>
      The simplest examples of continuous functions are the constant
      functions and the identity function <m>\mathrm{id}(x)=x</m>. We leave
      the justification of these statements as an exercise.
    </p>

    <proposition xml:id="prop-absolute-value-continuous">
      <statement>
        <p>
          The absolute value function is continuous on <m>\R</m>.
        </p>
      </statement>

      <proof>
        <p>
          Fix <m>c \in \R</m>. By the reverse triangle inequality,
          <me>\bigl||x|-|c|\bigr| \le |x-c| \quad (x \in \R).</me>
          Therefore, for any <m>\varepsilon \gt 0</m>, if <m>|x-c| \lt
          \varepsilon</m>, then <m>||x|-|c|| \lt \varepsilon</m> as well.
          Since <m>c</m> is an arbitrary real number, this shows that the
          function <m>x \mapsto |x|</m> is continuous on <m>\R</m>.
        </p>
      </proof>
    </proposition>

    <proposition xml:id="prop-reciprocal-continuous">
      <statement>
        <p>
          The reciprocal function <m>f(x)=1/x</m> is continuous on
          <m>\R \setminus \{0\}</m>.
        </p>
      </statement>

      <proof>
        <p>
          To prove the continuity of the function <m>x \mapsto 1/x</m>, we
          need, roughly speaking, to show that for any fixed <m>c \neq 0</m>,
          <me>\left|\frac{1}{x}-\frac{1}{c}\right|
            = \frac{|x-c|}{|x||c|}</me>
          is small whenever <m>|x-c|</m> is small. Thus, we need to make sure
          that the quantity <m>|xc|</m>, and hence <m>|x|</m>, stays bounded
          away from <m>0</m> when <m>x</m> is close to <m>c</m>. This can
          be achieved because if <m>|x-c| \lt |c|/2</m>, then
          <m>||x|-|c|| \lt |c|/2</m>, and that guarantees
          <m>|x| \gt |c|/2</m>. Thus,
          <me>\left|\frac{1}{x}-\frac{1}{c}\right| = \frac{|x-c|}{|x||c|}
          \le \frac{2|x-c|}{|c|^2}.</me>
          So for any <m>\varepsilon \gt 0</m>, if we choose
          <m>0 \lt \delta \lt \min\{|c|/2, \varepsilon|c|^2/2\}</m>, then the
          inequality above implies <m>|1/x - 1/c| \lt \varepsilon</m>, and we
          are done, since <m>c \neq 0</m> is arbitrary.
        </p>
      </proof>
    </proposition>

    <example xml:id="eg-continuous-functions-on-discrete-domains">
      <statement>
        <p>
          If the domain consists entirely of isolated points, then every
          function on that domain is continuous. For example, every function
          <m>f \colon \Z \to \R</m> is continuous, because each integer is an
          isolated point of <m>\Z</m>.
        </p>
      </statement>
    </example>

    <p>
      Later we will prove that sums, products, quotients (where the
      denominator is nonzero), and compositions of continuous functions are
      again continuous. From those general results it will follow that every
      polynomial is continuous on <m>\R</m>, every rational function is
      continuous on its domain, and standard functions such as
      <m>\sin x</m>, <m>\cos x</m>, <m>e^x</m>, and <m>\ln x</m> are
      continuous on their natural domains.
    </p>
  </subsection>
</section>
